  "rationale": "<p>The correct answer is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"60,000\"><mn>60,000</mn></math>. It&rsquo;s given that the weight of sample A is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"468 percent sign\"><mn>468</mn><mo>%</mo></math> of the weight of sample B&nbsp;and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"0.780 percent sign\"><mn>0.780</mn><mo>%</mo></math> of the weight of sample C. Let the weight of sample B be <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"b\"><mi>b</mi></math> and the weight of sample C be <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"c\"><mi>c</mi></math>. Then, the weight of sample A is equivalent to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"StartFraction 468 b Over 100 EndFraction\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>468</mn><mi>b</mi></mrow><mn>100</mn></mfrac></math>, or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"4.68 b\"><mn>4.68</mn><mi>b</mi></math>, and also equivalent to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"StartFraction 0 period 780 c Over 100 EndFraction\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>780</mn><mi>c</mi></mrow><mn>100</mn></mfrac></math>, or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"0.00780 c\"><mn>0.00780</mn><mi>c</mi></math>. Setting these expressions equal to each other yields <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"4.68 b equals 0.00780 c\"><mn>4.68</mn><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0.00780</mn><mi>c</mi></math>. Dividing both sides of this equation by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"0.00780\"><mn>0.00780</mn></math> yields&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"StartFraction 4.68 b Over 0.00780 EndFraction equals c\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>4.68</mn><mi>b</mi></mrow><mn>0.00780</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>c</mi></math>, or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"c equals 600 b\"><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>600</mn><mi>b</mi></math>. If the weight of sample C is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"p percent sign\"><mi>p</mi><mo>%</mo></math> of the weight of sample B, then <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"c equals StartFraction p Over 100 EndFraction b\"><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></mrow><mn>100</mn></mfrac><mi>b</mi></math>. Since <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"c equals 600 b\"><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>600</mn><mi>b</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"c equals StartFraction p Over 100 EndFraction b\"><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></mrow><mn>100</mn></mfrac><mi>b</mi></math>, it follows that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"600 b equals StartFraction p Over 100 EndFraction b\"><mn>600</mn><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></mrow><mn>100</mn></mfrac><mi>b</mi></math>, or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"600 equals StartFraction p Over 100 EndFraction\"><mn>600</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>p</mi><mn>100</mn></mfrac></math>. Multiplying both sides of this equation by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"100\"><mn>100</mn></math> yields <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"60,000 equals p\"><mn>60,000</mn><mo>=</mo><mi>p</mi></math>. Therefore, the value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"p\"><mi>p</mi></math> is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"60,000\"><mn>60,000</mn></math>.</p>",
